{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514037"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:18:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:18:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12266"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12266"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.21,0.19,0.27,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4788"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107305"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4788"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12266"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89768"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7663"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8694"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8794"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14422"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17692"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34864"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34875"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39895"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42726"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107305"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man attends his General Practice clinic for his annual health check-up. He has a medical history of asthma. He does not smoke but drinks wine occasionally. He reports that he is in good health and runs his own farm. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis GP arranges some routine blood tests. His fasting blood glucose level is 8.5 mmol/L (4.0-5.5). At the follow-up appointment to discuss the blood test results, a random blood glucose level is found to be 10.0 mmol/L (4.0-7.8).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["HbA1c","Repeat fasting blood glucose level","Oral glucose tolerance test","No further investigations required","Repeat random blood glucose level"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the updated Australian guidelines for the \u0022Management of type 2 diabetes: A handbook for general practice\u0022, the diagnosis of diabetes mellitus in an asymptomatic patient requires specific criteria to be met.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis criteria in an asymptomatic patient requires:\u003Cbr /\u003E\u2022 HbA1c \u22656.5% (48 mmol/mol) on two separate occasions \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003Eor\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cbr /\u003E\u2022 FBG \u22657.0 mmol/L or random blood glucose\u00a0\u226511.1 mmol/L confirmed by a second abnormal FBG on a separate day \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003Eor\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cbr /\u003E\u2022 OGTT before (fasting) and two hours after an oral 75 g glucose load is taken. Diabetes is diagnosed as FBG \u22657.0 mmol/L or two-hour post-challenge blood glucose \u226511.1 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is recommended that the same laboratory test be repeated when attempting to confirm a diagnosis, using a new blood sample, for a greater likelihood of concurrence of results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the most appropriate next step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat the fasting blood glucose level\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s initial fasting blood glucose level of 8.5 mmol/L is above the diagnostic threshold of 7.0 mmol/L. However, a single elevated reading is not sufficient for diagnosis. The guidelines state that a fasting blood glucose \u22657.0 mmol/L or random blood glucose \u226511.1 mmol/L needs to be confirmed by a second abnormal fasting blood glucose on a separate day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003EHbA1c\u003C/strong\u003E is an important test for monitoring diabetes and can be used for diagnosis, the guidelines recommend repeating the same laboratory test when attempting to confirm a diagnosis. Since the initial abnormal result was a fasting blood glucose, it is most appropriate to repeat this test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral glucose tolerance test\u003C/strong\u003E is another diagnostic option for diabetes, but it is not the preferred next step in this scenario. It would be more invasive and time-consuming than repeating the fasting blood glucose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further investigations\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate given the elevated fasting and random blood glucose levels, which strongly suggest diabetes and require confirmation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeating the random blood glucose level\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best choice because random levels are more variable and less reliable for diagnosis than fasting levels. Moreover, the patient\u0027s random level of 10.0 mmol/L does not meet the diagnostic threshold of \u226511.1 mmol/L for random glucose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while the patient lives remotely and attends the clinic infrequently, the need for a timely diagnosis of diabetes outweighs the inconvenience of an additional visit. The GP should emphasise the importance of returning for this repeat test as soon as possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce the diagnosis is confirmed with a second elevated fasting blood glucose, further investigations including HbA1c for baseline control assessment, and screening for complications would be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diagnosis of diabetes mellitus in an asymptomatic patient requires confirmation with a second abnormal fasting blood glucose level on a separate day."],"references":["Sapra A, Bhandari P. Diabetes Mellitus [Internet]. PubMed. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551501/#:~:text=According%20to%20the%20American%20Diabetes","Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Management of type 2 diabetes: A handbook for general practice [Internet]. 2020. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/41fee8dc-7f97-4f87-9d90-b7af337af778/Management-of-type-2-diabetes-A-handbook-for-general-practice.aspx","Standards of Medical Care in Diabetes - 2022. Diabetes Care January 2022 Vol 45 Supplement 1.  https://diabetesjournals.org/care/issue/45/Supplement_1."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89768"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12266"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89768"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-27T20:42:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-27T20:44:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4788"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107305"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG